{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473302"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2311"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.23,0.48,0.01,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2311"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA healthy couple attend the antenatal clinic. The woman is ten weeks pregnant. Their first child has cystic fibrosis (CF) and they want to know the risk of this child being affected with CF.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the appropriate test for the diagnosis of cystic fibrosis in this fetus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Newborn screening (Guthrie test)","Non invasive pregnancy screening (cell free DNA)","Chorionic villus sampling and molecular testing","Early morphology ultrasound","Carrier screening"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECystic fibrosis (CF) is chronic disease resulting in thickened mucous production from exocrine glands mainly involving the lungs and pancreas. Cystic fibrosis is an autosomal recessive condition caused by a mutation in the cystic fibrosis transmembrane regulator (CFTR) gene and affects cellular chloride channel function. It affects approximately 1:2500 children. In Australia, 1:35 people are carriers for CF and prenatal screening is available for all couples. If two people are genetic carriers the risk of having another affected child is 1:4. There is a 50% chance that the child will be a carrier (heterozygous) and a 25% chance that the child will not be a genetic carrier for CF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIdeally this couple would have been screened and counselled on the risks of CF in future pregnancies prior to this pregnancy. There is an option for preimplantation genetic diagnosis if IVF technologies are utilised. For the early diagnosis of CF in this fetus, \u003Cstrong\u003Echorionic villus sampling and molecular testing\u003C/strong\u003E of CFTR variants is recommended. Currently 178 variants of CFTR are tested for in prenatal testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enewborn screening (Guthrie test)\u003C/strong\u003E is a neonatal screening test that likely detected CF in the first child but is not the correct test for determining CF early in this pregnancy. Currently, \u003Cstrong\u003Enon invasive pregnancy screening (cell free DNA)\u003C/strong\u003E is not a diagnostic test for CF due to the rate of false positive and false negative results, however testing for the paternal mutation in the maternal cell free DNA (cfDNA) is progressing quickly and the potential of non-invasive cfDNA testing is increasing as a future option. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly morphology ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E will not diagnose CF, hyperechogenic fetal bowel is an ultrasound finding associated with CF but it is non-specific and would indicate that further molecular diagnostic testing for CF was necessary. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarrier screening\u003C/strong\u003E of the parents is incorrect as both parents must be carriers for their first child to be affected by CF.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chorionic villus sampling and molecular testing is recommended for the early diagnosis of cystic fibrosis in a foetus."],"references":["RANZCOG March 2019: Genetic Carrier Screening C-Obs 63. https://ranzcog.edu.au/RANZCOG_SITE/media/RANZCOG-MEDIA/Women%27s%20Health/Statement%20and%20guidelines/Clinical-Obstetrics/Genetic-carrier-screening(C-Obs-63)New-March-2019_1.pdf?ext=.pdf","Rieder, W., White, S., McGillivray, G. and Hui, L. (2018), Contemporary prenatal aneuploidy screening practice in Australia: Frequently asked questions in the cell\u2010free DNA era. Aust N Z J Obstet Gynaecol, 58: 397-403. https://doi.org/10.1111/ajo.12834","Muller F, Simon-Bouy B, Girodon E, Monnier N, Malinge MC, Serre JL; French Collaborative Group. Predicting the risk of cystic fibrosis with abnormal ultrasound signs of fetal bowel: results of a French molecular collaborative study based on 641 prospective cases. Am J Med Genet. 2002 Jun 15;110(2):109-15. doi: 10.1002/ajmg.10431. PMID: 12116247.","Natalie J Chandler, Helena Ahlfors, Suzanne Drury, Rhiannon Mellis, Melissa Hill, Fiona J McKay, Claire Collinson, Jane Hayward, Lucy Jenkins, Lyn S Chitty, Noninvasive Prenatal Diagnosis for Cystic Fibrosis: Implementation, Uptake, Outcome, and Implications, Clinical Chemistry, Volume 66, Issue 1, January 2020, Pages 207\u2013216, https://doi.org/10.1373/clinchem.2019.305011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-24T11:44:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-24T11:44:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2311"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","syno